@article{Lerner1981,
abstract = {The filamentous phage fl seems to establish a permanent infection in Escherichia coli, yet previous studies, using pulse labels, have failed to detect net RFI synthesis late in infection. We have shown by long-term labeling that RF synthesis at some level does continue even late in infection, but at a rate not reliably detectable with pulse labels. f1-Infected cells continue to grow and divide while steadily releasing phage. This does not reflect an intracellular steady state. Shortly after infection, the number of RF molecules per infected bacterium increases rapidly and then drops four- to fivefold. We have enumerated the number of RF molecules/IC by two independent techniques: transfection with DNA fractionated on sucrose gradients and by gel electrophoresis. By the transfection assay, we find 30 RF/IC early in infection and 5 RF/IC late in infection; the direct gel measurement yields 50 RF/IC early and 15 RF/IC late. We have also investigated the need for reinfection in maintaining the f1 "steady state" by examining phage growth in f1-transfected female (F-) cells. We find that f1 infection can be maintained in the absence of reinfection, but that uninfected cells segregate at a rate of one cell in every 10 generations. {\textcopyright} 1981.},
